<p class="p">The drying process may be described by Fick’s law:
 <disp-formula id="FD3-ijerph-14-00814" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">(4)</label>
  <math id="mm13" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <msup class="msup">
      <mover accent="true" class="mover">
       <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">m</mi>
       <mo class="mo">˙</mo>
      </mover>
      <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">"</mo>
     </msup>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <mo class="mo">−</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">D</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">w</mi>
     </msub>
     <mi class="mi">·</mi>
     <mi class="mi">dC</mi>
     <mo class="mo">/</mo>
     <mi class="mi">dx</mi>
     <mtext class="mtext"> </mtext>
     <mo class="mo">(</mo>
     <mi class="mi">kg</mi>
     <mo class="mo">/</mo>
     <msup class="msup">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">m</mi>
      <mn class="mn">2</mn>
     </msup>
     <mtext class="mtext"> </mtext>
     <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">s</mi>
     <mo class="mo">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> where 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="mm14" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <msup class="msup">
      <mover accent="true" class="mover">
       <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">m</mi>
       <mo class="mo">˙</mo>
      </mover>
      <mo stretchy="false" class="mo">"</mo>
     </msup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (kg/m
 <sup class="sup">2</sup> s) is the mass flux of water, 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="mm15" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">D</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">w</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (m
 <sup class="sup">2</sup>/s) is the diffusion coefficient of water, 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="mm16" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (kg/m
 <sup class="sup">3</sup>) is the water concentration and 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="mm17" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">x</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (m) is the distance, i.e., 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="mm18" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <mi class="mi">dC</mi>
     <mo class="mo">/</mo>
     <mi class="mi">dx</mi>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (kg/m
 <sup class="sup">3</sup> m) is the concen­tration gradient. The diffusion coefficient is increasing only slightly with temperature. Since the water vapor pressure increases nearly exponentially with temperature, the driving force of the drying process, illustrated by the length of the red vertical lines in 
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="ijerph-14-00814-f001" class="xref">Figure 1</xref>, is much greater indoors (at 22 °C) than outdoors (at −5 °C). The indoor air therefore dries the interior (wood, upholstery, cloths, etc.) towards the corresponding EMC-value.
</p>
